:The Real Books are among the standard texts for teaching the repertoire of American jazz music. These books are used in jazzs education programs in colleges and conservatories (indeed, the first Real Book Eds 1-5 were created at Berklee for that very purpose). It would be fair to say, however, that this is not an "errata" page per se but a page of differences between the two standard versions of the Real Books in most common use; the entry should arguably be retitled as such. As Adrignola points out, this is not a repost of earlier material but was generated by me from the source material independent of whatever was originally posted. Indeed, this was originally posted on Wikipedia but was deleted there as being something that belonged on Wikibooks, hence its posting here. As the author I will not vote for or against deletion, since my opinion is biased.--[[User:Cunamara|Cunamara]] ([[User talk:Cunamara|talk]]) 14:16, 20 July 2009 (UTC) :{{keep}} but retitle. As described by [[User:Cunamara|Cunamara]] these seem to fit as a textbook, and if he is going to develop them in that direction, I do think this seems to fit better here than elsewhere. Caveat: we'd expect some work on the actual meaning of the differences, rather than just a list of what the differences were. [[User:Chazz|Chazz]] <small>([[User talk:Chazz|talk]])</small> 16:00, 22 July 2009 (UTC)
