==Basic Limit Exercises==
{{question-answer|question=1. <math>\lim_{x\to 2} (4x^2 - 3x+1)</math>|answer=Since this is a polynomial, two can simply be plugged in. This results in <math>4(4)-2(3)+1=16-6+1=\mathbf{11}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=2. <math>\lim_{x\to 5} (x^2)</math>|answer=<math>5^2=\mathbf{25}</math>}}

==One-Sided Limits==

Evaluate the following limits or state that the limit does not exist.
{{question-answer|question=3. <math> \lim_{x\to 0^-} \frac{x^3+x^2}{x^3+2x^2} </math>|answer=Factor as <math>\frac{x^2}{x^2}\frac{x+1}{x+2}</math>.  In this form we can see that there is a removable discontinuity at x=0 and that the limit is <math>\mathbf{\frac{1}{2}}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=4. <math> \lim_{x\to 7^-} |x^2+x| -x </math>|answer=<math>|7^2+7|-7 = \mathbf{49}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=5. <math> \lim_{x\to -1^-} \sqrt{1-x^2}</math>|answer=<math>\sqrt{1-x^2}</math> is defined if <math>x^2<1</math>, so the limit is <math>\sqrt{1-1^2}=\mathbf{0}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=6. <math> \lim_{x\to -1^+} \sqrt{1-x^2}</math>|answer=<math>\sqrt{1-x^2}</math> is not defined if <math>x^2>1</math>, so '''the limit does not exist.'''}}

==Two-Sided Limits==

Evaluate the following limits or state that the limit does not exist.
{{question-answer|question=7. <math> \lim_{x \to -1} \frac{1}{x-1} </math>|answer=<math>\mathbf{-\frac{1}{2}}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=8. <math> \lim_{x\to 4}  \frac{1}{x-4} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to 4^-}  \frac{1}{x-4}=-\infty</math><br/><math> \lim_{x\to 4^+}  \frac{1}{x-4}=+\infty</math><br/>'''The limit does not exist.'''}}
{{question-answer|question=9. <math> \lim_{x\to 2}  \frac{1}{x-2} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to 2^-}  \frac{1}{x-2}=-\infty</math><br/><math> \lim_{x\to 2^+}  \frac{1}{x-2}=+\infty</math><br/>'''The limit does not exist.'''}}
{{question-answer|question=10. <math> \lim_{x\to -3}  \frac{x^2 - 9}{x+3} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to -3}  \frac{(x+3)(x-3)}{x+3} = \lim_{x\to -3}  x-3 = -3-3=\mathbf{-6}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=11. <math> \lim_{x\to 3} \frac{x^2 - 9}{x-3} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to 3} \frac{(x-3)(x+3)}{x-3} = \lim_{x\to 3} x+3 = 3+3 = \mathbf{6}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=12. <math> \lim_{x\to -1} \frac{x^2+2x+1}{x+1} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to -1} \frac{(x+1)(x+1)}{x+1} = \lim_{x\to -1} x+1 = -1+1 = \mathbf{0}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=13. <math> \lim_{x\to -1} \frac{x^3+1}{x+1} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to -1} \frac{(x^2-x+1)(x+1)}{x+1} = \lim_{x\to -1} x^2-x+1 = (-1)^2-(-1)+1 = 1+1+1 = \mathbf{3}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=14. <math> \lim_{x\to 4} \frac{x^2 + 5x-36}{x^2 - 16} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to 4} \frac{(x-4)(x+9)}{(x-4)(x+4)} = \lim_{x\to 4} \frac{x+9}{x+4} = \frac{4+9}{4+4} = \mathbf{\frac{13}{8}}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=15. <math> \lim_{x\to 25} \frac{x-25}{\sqrt{x}-5} </math>|answer=<math> \lim_{x\to 25} \frac{(\sqrt{x}-5)(\sqrt{x}+5)}{\sqrt{x}-5} = \lim_{x\to 25} \sqrt{x}+5) = \sqrt{25}+5) = 5+5 = \mathbf{10}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=16. <math> \lim_{x\to 0} \frac{\left|x\right|}{x} </math>|answer=<math>\lim_{x\to 0^-} \frac{\left|x\right|}{x} = \lim_{x\to 0^-} \frac{-x}{x} = \lim_{x\to 0^-} -1 = -1</math><br/><math>\lim_{x\to 0^+} \frac{\left|x\right|}{x} = \lim_{x\to 0^+} \frac{x}{x} = \lim_{x\to 0^+} 1 = 1</math><br/>'''The limit does not exist.'''}}
{{question-answer|question=17. <math> \lim_{x\to 2} \frac{1}{(x-2)^2} </math>|answer=As <math>x</math> approaches <math>2</math>, the denominator will be a very small positive number, so the whole fraction will be a very large positive number.  Thus, the limit is <math>\mathbf{\infty}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=18. <math> \lim_{x\to 3} \frac{\sqrt{x^2+16}}{x-3} </math>|answer=As <math>x</math> approaches <math>3</math>, the numerator goes to 5 and the denominator goes to 0.  Depending on whether you approach <math>3</math> from the left or the right, the denominator will be either a very small negative number, or a very small positive number.  So the limit from the left is <math>-\infty</math> and the limit from the right is <math>+\infty</math>.  Thus, '''the limit does not exist.'''}}
{{question-answer|question=19. <math> \lim_{x\to -2} \frac{3x^2-8x -3}{2x^2-18} </math>|answer=<math> \frac{3(-2)^2-8(-2) -3}{2(-2)^2-18} = \frac{3(4)+16-3}{2(4)-18} = \frac{12+16-3}{8-18} = \frac{25}{-10} = \mathbf{-\frac{5}{2}}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=20. <math> \lim_{x\to 2} \frac{x^2 + 2x + 1}{x^2-2x+1} </math>|answer=<math>\frac{2^2 + 2(2) + 1}{2^2-2(2)+1} = \frac{4 + 4 + 1}{4-4+1} = \frac{9}{1} = \mathbf{9}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=21. <math> \lim_{x\to 3} \frac{x+3}{x^2-9} </math>|answer=<math>\lim_{x\to 3} \frac{x+3}{(x+3)(x-3)} = \lim_{x\to 3} \frac{1}{x-3}</math><br/><math>\lim_{x\to 3^{-}} \frac{1}{x-3} = -\infty</math><br/><math>\lim_{x\to 3^{+}} \frac{1}{x-3} = +\infty</math><br/>'''The limit does not exist.'''}}
{{question-answer|question=22. <math> \lim_{x\to -1} \frac{x+1}{x^2+x} </math>|answer=<math>\lim_{x\to -1} \frac{x+1}{x(x+1)} = \lim_{x\to -1} \frac{1}{x} = \frac{1}{-1} = \mathbf{-1}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=23. <math> \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{1}{x^2+1} </math>|answer=<math>\frac{1}{1^2+1} = \frac{1}{1+1} = \mathbf{\frac{1}{2}}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=24. <math> \lim_{x\to 1} x^3 + 5x - \frac{1}{2-x} </math>|answer=<math>1^3 + 5(1) - \frac{1}{2-1} = 1 + 5 - \frac{1}{1} = 6 - 1 = \mathbf{5}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=25. <math> \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{x^2-1}{x^2+2x-3} </math>|answer=<math>\lim_{x\to 1} \frac{(x-1)(x+1)}{(x-1)(x+3)} = \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{x+1}{x+3} = \frac{1+1}{1+3} = \frac{2}{4} = \mathbf{\frac{1}{2}}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=26. <math> \lim_{x\to 1} \frac{5x}{x^2+2x-3} </math>|answer=Notice that as <math>x</math> approaches <math>1</math>, the numerator approaches <math>5</math> while the denominator approaches <math>0</math>.  However, if you approach from below, the denominator is negative, and if you approach from above, the denominator is positive.  So the limits from the left and right will be <math>-\infty</math> and <math>+\infty</math> respectively.  Thus, '''the limit does not exist.'''}}

==Limits to Infinity==

Evaluate the following limits or state that the limit does not exist.
{{question-answer|question=27. <math> \lim_{x\to \infty} \frac{-x + \pi}{x^2 + 3x + 2} </math>|answer=This rational function is bottom-heavy, so the limit is <math>\mathbf{0}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=28. <math> \lim_{x\to -\infty} \frac{x^2+2x+1}{3x^2+1} </math>|answer=This rational function has evenly matched powers of <math>x</math> in the numerator and denominator, so the limit will be the ratio of the coefficients, i.e. <math>\mathbf{\frac{1}{3}}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=29. <math> \lim_{x\to -\infty} \frac{3x^2 + x}{2x^2 - 15} </math>|answer=Balanced powers in the numerator and denominator, so the limit is the ratio of the coefficients, i.e. <math>\mathbf{\frac{3}{2}}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=30. <math> \lim_{x\to -\infty} 3x^2-2x+1 </math>|answer=This is a top-heavy rational function, where the exponent of the ratio of the leading terms is <math>2</math>.  Since it is even, the limit will be <math>\mathbf{\infty}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=31. <math> \lim_{x\to \infty} \frac{2x^2-32}{x^3-64} </math>|answer=Bottom-heavy rational function, so the limit is <math>\mathbf{0}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=32. <math> \lim_{x\to \infty} 6 </math>|answer=This is a rational function, as can be seen by writing it in the form <math>\frac{6x^0}{1x^0}</math>.  Since the powers of <math>x</math> in the numerator and denominator are evenly matched, the limit will be the ratio of the coefficients, i.e. <math>\mathbf{6}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=33. <math> \lim_{x\to \infty} \frac{3x^2 +4x}{x^4+2} </math>|answer=Bottom-heavy, so the limit is <math>\mathbf{0}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=34. <math> \lim_{x\to -\infty} \frac{2x+3x^2+1}{2x^2+3} </math>|answer=Evenly matched highest powers of <math>x</math> in the numerator and denominator, so the limit will be the ratio of the corresponding coefficients, i.e. <math>\mathbf{\frac{3}{2}}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=35. <math> \lim_{x\to -\infty} \frac{x^3-3x^2+1}{3x^2+x+5} </math>|answer=Top-heavy rational function, where the exponent of the ratio of the leading terms is <math>1</math>, so the limit is <math>\mathbf{-\infty}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=36. <math> \lim_{x\to \infty} \frac{x^2+2}{x^3-2} </math>|answer=Bottom-heavy, so the limit is <math>\mathbf{0}</math>.}}

==Limits of Piecewise Functions==

Evaluate the following limits or state that the limit does not exist.<br/>
</br>
37. Consider the function
: <math> f(x) = \begin{cases} (x-2)^2 & \mbox{if }x<2 \\ x-3 & \mbox{if }x\geq 2. \end{cases} </math>
{{question-answer|question=a. <math> \lim_{x\to 2^-}f(x) </math>|answer=<math>(2-2)^2 = \mathbf{0}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=b. <math> \lim_{x\to 2^+}f(x) </math>|answer=<math>2-3 = \mathbf{-1}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=c. <math> \lim_{x\to 2}f(x) </math>|answer=Since the limits from the left and right don't match, '''the limit does not exist.'''}}
<br/>
38. Consider the function
: <math> g(x) = \begin{cases} -2x+1 & \mbox{if }x\leq 0 \\ x+1 & \mbox{if }0<x<4 \\ x^2 +2 & \mbox{if }x \geq 4. \end{cases} </math>
{{question-answer|question=a. <math> \lim_{x\to 4^+} g(x) </math>|answer=<math>4^2+2 = 16+2 = \mathbf{18}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=b. <math> \lim_{x\to 4^-} g(x) </math>|answer=<math>4+1 = \mathbf{5}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=c. <math> \lim_{x\to 0^+} g(x) </math>|answer=<math>0+1 = \mathbf{1}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=d. <math> \lim_{x\to 0^-} g(x) </math>|answer=<math>-2(0)+1 = \mathbf{1}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=e. <math> \lim_{x\to 0} g(x) </math>|answer=Since the left and right limits match, the overall limit is also <math>\mathbf{1}</math>.}}
{{question-answer|question=f. <math> \lim_{x\to 1} g(x) </math>|answer=<math>1+1 = \mathbf{2}</math>}}
<br/>
39. Consider the function
: <math> h(x) = \begin{cases} 2x-3 & \mbox{if }x<2 \\ 8 & \mbox{if }x=2 \\ -x+3 & \mbox{if } x>2. \end{cases} </math>
{{question-answer|question=a. <math> \lim_{x\to 0} h(x) </math>|answer=<math>2(0)-3 = \mathbf{-3}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=b. <math> \lim_{x\to 2^-} h(x) </math>|answer=<math>2(2)-3 = 4-3 = \mathbf{1}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=c. <math> \lim_{x\to 2^+} h(x) </math>|answer=<math>-(2)+3 = \mathbf{1}</math>}}
{{question-answer|question=d. <math> \lim_{x\to 2} h(x) </math>|answer=Since the limits from the right and left match, the overall limit is <math>\mathbf{1}</math>.  Note that in this case, the limit at 2 does not match the function value at 2, so the function is discontinuous at this point.}}

